          {
            "type": "header",
            "text": "Urinalysis Interpretation",
            "level": 2
          },
          {
            "type": "list",
            "items": [
              { "text": "Bacteria / Pus cells: Pyelonephritis" },
              { "text": "Eosinophils: Acute Interstitial Nephritis" },
              { "text": "RBC Casts: Acute Glomerulonephritis / Leptospirosis" },
              { "text": "RBC (No casts): Renal artery/vein occlusion or Stones" },
              { "text": "Free Hb / No RBC: Intravascular Haemolysis (G6PD, Malaria, Transfusion)" }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "title": "Key Points",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "header",
            "text": "Key Points",
            "level": 2
          },
          {
            "type": "list",
            "items": [
              { "text": "Always exclude urinary tract obstruction first (palpate bladder, USS)." },
              { "text": "Distinguishing Pre-renal from Renal failure is vital; Pre-renal responds to fluids, Renal (ATN) does not (and fluids may cause overload)." },
              { "text": "In established Renal Failure (ATN), manage complications: Hyperkalaemia, Acidosis, and Fluid Overload." },
              { "text": "Indications for Dialysis: Refractory Hyperkalaemia (>6.5), Severe Metabolic Acidosis, Pulmonary Oedema, Uraemic Encephalopathy/Pericarditis." }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }
